<font color="#FF0000">THANKS FOR YOUR WISDOM</font><br>
<tt>Mon Nov  3 15:37:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Thank you All!!!  Your words of wisdom are a tremendous help.  Finding balance has been so difficult, because I've been ricocheting back and forth between trying to satisfy my needs and understanding his reasons for his sometimes irratic behavior.  Man!! What a field for growth - my own.  I understand the dangers of getting entrapped in codependence and have to continually remind myself to focus on my own life and learning.  <br><br>
Art, your explanation was very helpful.  One question...after you've moved out of the distortion, do you ever get a clear, solid base to stand on or do the same areas continue to become distorted when your emotions kick in?  Is there anything or type of response that is effective at kicking you out of it?<br><br>
A question to all of you...when he distorts things, do I just ignore it and say nothing, or do I point it out at the time or do I wait and point it out later when he's calmer and risk blowing it up all over again?  What has been more effective in your lives?  Paul, you said to talk to him at quiet times - does that mean to ignore it when he's into the unreasonable emotions?<br><br>
I saw a big shift in my way of approaching things this weekend and with it our relationship seemed to shift.  The only change was in my attitude - I thank all of you for that - God, it feels good to have someone to talk to - your support and concern is valued more than I can say.
<p><code>--   (Beth) </code><p>


